node.title: As the storm system moves toward Canada, its wind gusts taper.
node.alt: An overturned tractor-trailer on Interstate 80 near Anita, Iowa, on Wednesday.
node.description: The system that caused a chaotic night across the Midwest is moving north.
node.content: ["The storm system that cut across the central United States was heading toward southern Canada late Wednesday as its ferocious wind gusts began to subside, forecasters said.", "The system will race north of the Great Lakes on Thursday, the National Weather Service predicted on Wednesday evening. Gusty winds across the region would slowly diminish around the same time, the service said in a separate forecast.", "Tornado watches that had been in effect on Wednesday night in at least eight states expired as dangerously high winds mostly died down. The watches were a result of a storm system that formed in the Four Corners region \u2014 where Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico meet.", "Still, as many communities saw a reprieve from high winds on Wednesday night, people in southern Minnesota were reeling from fresh gusts of up to 70 miles per hour. Parts of Minnesota, Iowa and South Dakota were under a winter weather advisory until 3 a.m. local time.", "Aaron Jayjack, a storm chaser in Minnesota, posted a video on Twitter on Wednesday evening that showed sheets of snow blowing horizontally across the night sky.", "\u201cReally ripping at times here in Alexandria, Minnesota,\u201d he wrote in another post after midnight. \u201cNot a lot of cars out. Roads are slick. Slushy underneath, snow on top.\u201d"]
